SIMPLE: harass
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Harass
<hw>Har"ass</hw> <pr>(h⟦acr⟧r"⟦ait⟧s <it>or</it> h⟦adot⟧*r⟦acr⟧s")</pr>,
<pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Harassed</conjf> <pr>(h⟦acr⟧r"⟦ait⟧st <it>or</it>
h⟦adot⟧*r⟦acr⟧st")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Harassing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>harasser</ets>; cf.
OF. <ets>harace</ets> a basket made of cords, <ets>harace</ets>,
<ets>harasse</ets>,a very heavy and large shield; or <ets>harer</ets> to
set (a dog) on.]</ety> <def>To fatigue; to tire with repeated and
exhausting efforts; esp., to weary by importunity, teasing, or fretting;
to cause to endure excessive burdens or anxieties; -- sometimes followed
by <xex>out</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Troops] <qex>harassed</qex> with a long and wearisome march.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nature oppressed and <qex>harass'd</qex> out with care.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Vext with lawyers and <qex>harass'd</qex> with debt.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To weary; jade; tire; perplex; distress; tease;
worry; disquiet; chafe; gall; annoy; irritate; plague; vex; molest;
trouble; disturb; torment.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Harass</ent>⟦br⟧

